Git is a version control system used to track changes in your code.
It helps multiple people work on the same project without overwriting each other’s work.
COMMON GIT TERMS:
Term	Meaning
Repository (repo)	A folder where your project files and their version history are stored.
Commit	A snapshot of your project’s changes.
Branch	A separate line of development.
Merge	Combining changes from one branch into another.
Clone	Copying a remote repository to your local computer.
Push	Sending your local commits to a remote repository (like GitHub).
Pull	Fetching and merging changes from a remote repository to your local one.
Remote	A link to a repository hosted elsewhere (e.g., on GitHub).

BASIC COMMANDS:
Command    	          Description
git init	          Initialize a new Git repository.
git clone <url>	          Copy (clone) a remote repository to your local system.
git status	          Show current changes and tracked files.
git add <file>	          Add a file to the staging area.
git commit -m             "message"	Save (commit) your changes with a message.
git log	                  Show the history of commits.
git branch	          List branches in your repo.
git checkout <branch>	  Switch to a different branch.
git merge <branch>	  Merge another branch into your current one.
git push	          Upload local commits to the remote repo.
git pull	          Download and merge updates from remote repo.

